This void has an uneven floor that has not been boarded. It is unlit and there are small cable runs. PUDDING MILL LANE AUTOTRANSFORMER FEEDER STATION <PML ATFS> IS DIVIDED INTO 2 PARTS; 1> RAIL FOR LONDON <RFL> EQUIPMENT AND 2> NETWORK RAIL <NR> EQUIPMENT. THERE ARE SOME PARTS OF THE SUB-STATION <IE, CURRENT AND VOLTAGE TRANSFORMERS AND SOME INTERCONNECTING WIRING> THAT ARE SHARED AND THEREFORE CONNECT THE 2 PARTS OF PML ATFS TOGETHER. NR MAINTAINER TO BE MADE AWARE OF THIS & TO GAIN APPROPRIATE CIRCUIT AND EQUIPMENT ISOLATIONS PRIOR TO COMMENCING WORK. TEST BEFORE TOUCH MANDATORY.
PUDDING MILL LANE AUTOTRANSFORMER FEEDER STATION DOES NOT HAVE COMPOUND LIGHTING. SLIPS, TRIPS AND FALL HAZARD UNTIL TASK LIGHTING IS ESTABLISHED BY OPERATIVES.

PUDDING MILL LANE AUTOTRANSFORMER FEEDER STATION <PML ATFS> CONTAINS 2NO. RISER SHAFTS THAT RUN VERTICALLY AND DIRECTLY IN TO THE CROSSRAIL CENTRAL TUNNELS BENEATH PML ATFS. THESE ARE NORMALLY COVERED WITH A SUITABLY PURPOSED COVER, HOWEVER CARE MUST BE TAKEN WORKING ON OR AROUND THE RISERS WITH OPEN LIDS

THE STEEL PALISADE FENCE AROUND PUDDING MILL LANE AUTOTRANSFORMER FEEDER STATION IS TOPPED WITH AN ELECTRIC FENCE. THIS FENCE NEEDS TO BE ISOLATED <SEE OPERATION & MAINTENANCE MANUAL> TO ALLOW WORKING ON THE FENCE OR ELECTRIC FENCE OR WITHIN A SAFE DISTANCE OF THE FENCE.

PUDDING MILL LANE AUTOTRANSFORMER FEEDER STATION <PML ATFS> PROVIDES 25KV ELECTRICAL POWER TO BOTH THE CROSSRAIL CENTRAL TUNNELS AND THE GREAT EASTERN MAIN LINE <GEML>. THE TRACTION EARTH RETURN SYSTEM FROM THE CENTRAL TUNNELS IS TERMINATED ON THE SAME RETURN CURRENT BUS BAR <RCBB> AS THE TRACTION EARTH RETURN FROM THE GEML. TO WORK ON THE RCBB, BOTH THE CENTRAL TUNNELS AND GEML REQUIRE ISOLATION. THIS IS DOCUMENTED IN THE OPERATION & MAINTENANCE MANUAL, ROMFORD ELECTRICAL CONTROL ROOM INSTRUCTIONS AND A LOCAL DISTRIBUTION WORK INSTRUCTION.

PUDDING MILL LANE AUTOTRANSFORMER FEEDER STATION <PML ATFS> HAS 2NO. HIGH VOLTAGE CABLE CHAMBERS <4MX4MX4M APPROX>. 1NO. CHAMBER IS IN THE ADJACENT RAIL FOR LONDON <RFL> SITE. BOTH WILL COME UNDER NETWORK RAIL MAINTENANCE RESPONSIBILITY. BOTH CHAMBERS ARE USUALLY FULL OF WATER <AS BELOW THE WATER TABLE>. ACCESS TO EACH REQUIRES THEM TO BE FIRST PUMPED DRY OVER 24 HOURS. DURING THIS TIME PART OF THE CHAMBER COVER WILL BE OPEN. THERE IS RESIDUAL RISK AT SITE WITH THESE CONFINED SPACES AND DEEP WATER. ACCESS TO THESE CHAMBERS IS REQUIRED EVERY 12 MONTHS TO VISUALLY INSPECT THE HV CABLES BY NETWORK RAIL MAINTAINER.

PUDDING MILL LANE AUTOTRANSFORMER FEEDER STATION <PM ATFS> PROVIDES 25KV ELECTRICAL POWER TO BOTH THE CROSSRAIL CENTRAL TUNNELS AND THE GREAT EASTERN MAIN LINE <GEML>. THE SWITCHGEAR TO THE CENTRAL TUNNELS ARE OPERATED BY ATC/CROSSRAIL LTD. SOON TO BE RFL AT ROMFORD CONTROL CENTRE <RCC>; WHILST THE SWITCHGEAR FEEDING THE GEML AND THE SWITCHGEAR BETWEEN NATIONAL GRID AND PML ATFS ARE OPERATED BY NETWORK RAIL AT ROMFORD ELECTRICAL CONTROL ROOM <ECR> IN THE RCC. THE RFL SWITCHGEAR IS FENCED OFF FROM THE REMAINDER OF THE NETWORK RAIL PML ATFS COMPOUND, BUT THERE REMAINS THE POSSIBILITY THAT RFL COULD OPERATE THEIR SWITCHGEAR WHILST NETWORK RAIL <NR> MAINTAINERS ARE AT PML ATFS MAINTAINING/OPERATING THE NR PORTION OF THE SITE. THERE ARE ELECTRICAL CONTROL ROOM INSTRUCTIONS <ECRI> AND WORK INSTRUCTION <WI> PROCEDURES TO CONTROL ACCESS AND WAYS OF WORKING, BUT OPERATIVES ENTERING PML ATFS SHOULD BE AWARE AND KEEP AWAY FROM THE RFL SWITCHGEAR.

Limited records of gas supply pipelines are held by the Senior Asset Manager and the Facility Delivery Manager. All mains gas supply pipes up to and including the meter are the responsibility of National Grid. In case of emergency station has contact details. Natural gas is non-toxic, but large concentrations could cause suffocation. It is highly flammable and leakage from a pipeline could result in an explosive mixture with air. Noise of escaping gas could be sufficient to cause damage to hearing and ear protection must be worn. All persons must be kept 100 metres from the damaged pipeline.

Located at platforms. Each platform has a Low Voltage Switch Rooms. These rooms have Limited Access and extensive electrical equipment resulting in electrocution hazards. There is also cabling at height, which could lead to hazards from working at height and falling objects.
There is no fixed access to the canopy and all roof areas should be considered as potentially fragile.

The Cleaning compound is located off the main concourse on the opposite side from the Customer Service Office. The area stores cleaning materials and equipment and for the recharging of the floor cleaning equipment. There is also a sink, hot water heater and cleaning operative's lockers. Three of the walls are partition walls. Within this compound is an access door to the BT Police CCTV camera switch room.

25,000-volt AC electric traction supply cables, from overhead wires, electrify all tracks at Fenchurch Street Station. All works undertaken on the station must be undertaken in accordance with the Network Rail instructions concerning personal safety on electrified lines

There are no 3rd or 4th rail electric conductor rails at this station. Note: Portable metal steps and ladders <electrical conductors> are specially banned from Fenchurch Street Station in order to avoid the danger of contact with traction supply equipment.

There are many areas above rooms located throughout Fenchurch Street Station. Typical rooms contain obvious common electrical hazards in the form of high and low voltage electrical cables, associated switchgear, control panels and cabinets. Fire alarm system control panels are often also present. There are often no warning signs on entry doors indicating equipment voltages but access is restricted to authorised personnel only.

The pipe is 220mm diameter Cast Iron and sits approximately 0.75m below ground level. It is suspected to be redundant however this has not been confirmed by any testing. The function and source of the pipe is not known. Various attempts were made to trace the pipe however they were not successful. It is suspected to be foul drainage related to a nearby malting house or previous redundant sidings however these assumptions were not confirmed. A drawing markup is attached showing its approximate location. The pipe was uncovered beneath the maintenance access track approx 3.4m from the redundant platform wall, it extends towards the London end and bends beneath the platform approx 40m to the wast. The pipe was traced and is suspected to run east through the car park past the station building, it is then suspected to connect to the south to the vegetated area.           ~

Equipment or Lookout Safe Systems of Work shall only be used if all the conditions below are satisfied:~
1.  Work shall be more than 1.25m from the nearest open line and all personnel shall be at least 1.25m from the nearest open line at all times~
2.  Personnel shall be in possession of a certificate of competence in personal track safety approved by RfL in accordance with LO-MS-102-02-0001 Access to the Railway.~
3.  Trains shall be travelling no faster than 40mph~
4.  Work shall stop as a train passes~
5.  Work shall only take place during daylight with clear visibility. Restricted sighting and limited places of safety.~
The condition allows working on the CESS path and beyond while trains are running.

The Boiler Room contains Gas, Hot/Cold Water and Electricity services, which present potential hazards of explosion, asphyxiation, scolding and electrocution. It has a high ceiling and the boilers produce significant levels of noise and may cause a high Personal Dose if work was carried out over a protracted period. Pipes cross the walking access routes at approximately 1.8m resulting in a potential for head injuries.

Situated to the left when entering from the main entrance at Fenchurch Place. Redundant waste pipes from Nat West building above and small narrow switch room may be present. There are main cable runs and lagged pipework high above and also in a shaft, accessed through the removed blocks in a dividing wall. To enter this shaft confined space must be considered. There is a drop to the floor level below <distance unknown>. Consideration must be given to areas classified as Limited Access and Confined Space <The Confined Spaces Regulations 1997> must be met, please apply Clauses 1 & 2 Monitoring of access paperwork. Hazard/Risk Assessment to be carried out for activity - Results of assessment will determine control measures. Air monitoring before entry. Breathing apparatus to be available for rescue.
High Voltage Switch Rooms has not been accessed but is reported to constitute a Limited Access area and presents hazards relating to electrocution.

Medium Voltage Switch Room has not been accessed and presents hazards relating to electrocution. In addition there is a caged area containing transformer equipment which also constitutes hazards relating to electrocution.
A Gas cupboard is situated near the road access. All gas services constitute potential explosion and asphyxiation hazards.

AS STAFF HAVE TO GO THROUGH NCP CAR PARK TO GET TO NR ACCESS GATE, THERE IS AN ANPR CAMERA WHICH IS CAPTURING VEHICLES AND SENDING OUT FINES. IT HAS BEEN AGREED WITH NCP MANAGER THAT WE WILL SUPPLY A FLEET LIST WHICH THEY WILL ADD TO THEIR CAMERA. HOWEVER, ALL VEHICLES PASSING THROUGH THE CAR PARK MUST PARK IN THE COMPOUND AT THE END, AND NOT IN THE NCP CAR PARK. AS YOU WILL BE FINED IF CAUGHT PARKING IN THE CAR PARK. WE HAVE MADE THE MANAGER AWARE THAT IT MAY NOT ALWAYS BE POSSIBLE TO GIVE ADVANCE WARNING OF WORKS DUE TO EMERGENCY CALL-OUTS OR FAULTS, IN WHICH CASE WE STILL SEND OVER VEHICLE REGISTRATIONS RETROSPECTIVELY.

Special sets of Insulated Rail Joints <IRJ> exist at each end of the incline single line. No train or vehicle should stand over these IRJ simultaneously; however, it is possible for legitimate non-conflicting routes to be established from Kings Cross <KX> and Camden Road Signalboxes which would enable this situation.~ To avoid this, the KX signaller must immediately be advised if a train is positioned, or to be moved, over the IRJ between Track Circuits <TC> T1232 & T1213 at Camden Road or if the IRJ between these TC fails. The KX signaller must not then allow a movement across the IRJ between TC XNB & T.007 on KX panel.~ Equally, if KX advises that a train is positioned or to be moved over the IRJ between <TC> XNB & T.007 or that the IRJ has failed, no movement is to be authorised across the IRJ between TC T1232 & T1213 at Camden Road~ Special arrangements will need to be considered by the Possession Planner/PICOP if one or more of these IRJ?s are included within a Possession.

Equipment or Lookout Safe Systems of Work shall only be used if all the conditions below are satisfied:~
1.  Work shall be more than 1.25m from the nearest open line and all personnel shall be at least 1.25m from the nearest open line at all times~
2.  Personnel shall be in possession of a certificate of competence in personal track safety approved by RfL in accordance with LO-MS-102-02-0001 Access to the Railway.~

New type of level crossing warning system installed which provides warnings for users . Red lights and Yodalarms are provided together with rail mounted sensors at the crossing . Equipment cases are provided and the system is powered . No electrical hazard exists from sensors, connecting  cabling , lights or yodalarm systems but risk does exist for the power cables supplying the system .The system is remotely monitored and automatically reports system failures and component damage to route control .  Staff should NOT rely on the system to warn of trains . Staff should not touch any of the equipment unless they are authorised and competent to do so . Any damage caused to the system or any of its components should be reported immediately to Control .

Confirmed Bat roost within the Signal Box. Bat survey undertaken by JBA in 2013 prior to the decommissioning of the signal box identified pippistrelle bat droppings within the roof void of the signal box. The droppings were found within the main roof void and the void above the kitchen. Three bat emergence surveys were undertaken but no bats were recorded emerging. It was concluded that the building has been in use as a summer bat roost. A bat licence from Natural England would be required if this building were to be demolished or works were undertaken that would affect the roof or the roof void. The bat reports can be accessed via Moss, type into the search National Records Group Ecology Studies and then look for a report titled Ely-Norwich Re-signalling - Bat Activity Survey Shippea Hill.

Noise Abatement Zone~
Noise to be kept to a minimum due to proximity of residential properties

Equipment or Lookout Safe Systems of Work shall only be used if all the conditions below are satisfied~
1.  Work shall be more than 1.25m from the nearest open line and all personnel shall be at least 1.25m from the nearest open line at all times~
2.  Personnel shall be in possession of a certificate of competence in personal track safety approved by RfL in accordance with LO-MS-102-02-0001 Access to the Railway.~
3.  Trains shall be travelling no faster than 40mph~
4.  Work shall stop as a train passes~
5.  Work shall only take place during daylight with clear visibility - "Restricted sighting and limited places of safety - Dalston station to Highbury & Islington buffer stop.
The condition allows working on the CESS path and beyond while trains are running.  There are limited locations between Dalston Western Curve and Highbury and Islington."

CABLES INSTALLED IN SECURED CABLE ROUTES WITH HV WARNING SIGNS. CABLE ROUTE VARIETY OF DIFFERENT TYPES: BURIED ROUTE, GROUND LEVEL, RAISED ON POSTS <1M HIGH> & WALLED MOUNTED AT HEIGHTS 0.5M-3M ABOVE RAIL LEVEL. STAFF SHOULD NOT WALK/LEAN ON CABLE ROUTES TO AVOID ELECTROMAGNETIC FIELDS EXPOSURE ABOVE SAFE LIMITS. WHERE INSTALLED ON RAISED POSTS, ONCOMING TRAINS ESCAPE IMPEDED. OLD UKPN OIL FILLED CABLES WITH ASSOCIATED PILOT CABLES CAN BE FOUND IN BOTH CESSES BETWEEN CHADWELL HEATH AND SHENFIELD. THESE CABLES ARE REDUNDANT 33KV ELECTRICITY SUPPLY INDUSTRY <DNO> CABLES. THE CABLES CAN BECOME LIVE IN AN EVENT OF DEWIREMENT OR ELECTRO MAGNETIC INDUCTION, AND MIGHT CONTAIN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. UNTIL THE CABLES ARE FULLY REMOVED, AVOID THE CABLES AS FAR AS PRACTICABLE AND WEAR PROTECTIVE GLOVES AT ALL TIMES. SEEK ADVICE FROM E&P ROUTE ENGINEER BEFORE ANY WORKS ON OR NEAR THE CABLE. The Boiler House is located within the plant room <83> on platform 18. The 3 boilers are on a raised level within the plant room.The plant room contains boilers and pumps associated with the main hot water system, the cold-water storage tank and switchgear. There is a large diameter mains gas supply in the boiler house feeding the operational boilers in a side room off room 83. A second boiler room is located on the trolley route Room 28 and contains 6 boilers and associated equipment together with switchgear and a control panel. Distribution Schematics for this operation are shown on the wall.

Various service equipment located at Fenchurch Place, Station entrance by retail outlets. A switch room within the Superdrug premises which houses a telephone enhancer, a distribution switch board and electricity meter for "FENNS", the sandwich bar adjacent to Superdrug. There is an inspection cover on the pavement. It is not known which services it contains or how deep it is.

Within the leased premises, offices, storerooms etc, there is a suspended ceiling with a void above containing various services. These can be accessed from the hatch in the Telecoms Switch room. This area has low headroom. Consideration must be given to areas classified as Limited Access and Confined Space <The Confined Spaces Regulations 1997> must be met, please apply Clauses 1 & 2 Monitoring of access paperwork. Hazard/Risk Assessment to be carried out for activity - Results of assessment will determine control measures. Air monitoring before entry. Breathing apparatus to be available for rescue.

Air Conditioning Units located to the side of the marked walkway and behind handrails. These serve retail unit.The ventilation duct from below ground level at the end of the walkway would indicate basement services. The access for these are unknown but if found should be considered a confined space. CCTV cameras monitor the area. Any work taking place in this area must recognise the need to keep the walkway clear for use.Consideration must be given to areas classified as Confined Space <The Confined Spaces Regulations 1997> must be met, please apply Clauses 2 Monitoring of access paperwork. Hazard/Risk Assessment to be carried out for activity - Results of assessment will determine control measures. Air monitoring before entry. Breathing apparatus to be available for rescue

Located at Tower exit at Coopers Row, within the fire exit of No.1 America Square. The shaft is very narrow and houses the shutter mechanism and the recess above is where the motor is located. Access to this area is by agreement with the occupiers of No.1 America Square and any work activity taking place must not be in conflict with that of the occupants. There are other obvious risks of entanglement and falls.

The void behind plasma screeners at Tower Hill exit. This is a narrow unlit space between a concrete wall and a false wall. This is a limited access with extremely limited space for manoeuvre with numerous cable runs, pipework, false wall space bars and fire hose. The hazards in this area are electricity related. Consideration must be given to areas classified as Limited Access please apply Clauses 1 Monitoring of access paperwork. Hazard/Risk Assessment to be carried out for activity - Results of assessment will determine control measures.

Accessed from the subway between the platforms & from the Towerhill entrance stairway.Within the room a small unused cupboard below the stairway has low headroom. At the opposite end of the Locker Room is a door that is kept locked. It leads to a room that is only partially lit and has a floor with a number of different levels containing narrow access corridors for services. Beyond this there is low headroom and an unlit area. Another locked door gives access to cable runs and pipework from a very narrow ledge. The access door keys are kept in a safe deposit box in the Station Manager's Office. Consideration must be given to areas classified as Limited Access please apply Clauses 1 Monitoring of access paperwork. Hazard/Risk Assessment to be carried out for activity - Results of assessment will determine control measures.

There are two platforms, each with voids below and columns either supporting the buildings above or the canopies. There are a number of inspection covers giving access to the area below the platforms. This is thought to be a shallow space providing drainage pipework and cable runs likely to be electrical and biological hazards. Consideration must be given to areas classified as Limited Access and Confined Space <The Confined Spaces Regulations 1997> must be met, please apply Clauses 1 & 2 Monitoring of access paperwork. Hazard/Risk Assessment to be carried out for activity - Results of assessment will determine control measures. Air monitoring before entry. Breathing apparatus to be available for rescue.

The room leads in from French Ordinary Court bin area. Air conditioning ducting near the entrance is at head level and pipework and cable runs on the walls. There is an electrical distribution board in one corner and a caged meter in another. The Bin Room has a rubbish chute from the ceiling and normally a rubbish bin is positioned below it. If it is necessary to move the bin then the rubbish chute shield should be placed over the chute opening to prevent rubbish falling through. This area has an obvious attraction for vermin and persons working in this area should be aware of Weil's disease as well as the more obvious biological, electrical and head bumping hazards.

All tracks have overhead 25,000-volt AC electric traction supply cables. All works undertaken on the station must be undertaken in accordance with the Network Rail instructions concerning personal safety on electrified line.

There are numerous power cable runs of both high and low voltage above and below ground level throughout the station. Each contractor will be responsible for the scanning of the work site in order to locate the exact location of the underground power cable

To the right on entering the Boiler Room is the Gas Meter Room <R051>. This contains the main gas control valve and the gas meter. Within this room the hazards are gas related e.g. leaks etc. Beyond the entrance to the Boiler Room is a stairway leading down into the main level of the Boiler Room, containing the heating boilers and related pumps and electrical distribution board. It is not known if any of the lagging contains asbestos.Adjoining the Boiler Room is Room R048 which is the Main Switch Room containing the main distribution board. There is a fire exit from the Boiler Room into this Switch Room and another from the switch Room into the Nat West basement and the door facing leads to St Catherine's Row.

Water mains and meter located in front of retail outlets at main entrance to station. Limited records of water supply pipelines are held by the Senior Asset Manager and the Facility Delivery Manager. Contractors should note that these would be present to most areas of the station, including platforms.

Hot water is distributed and supplied to the "Raven Bar" and "Upper Crust" by means of a network of pipes many of which are lagged. Other locations have their own individual electric hot water heaters.

Records of gas supply pipelines are held by the Senior Asset Manager and the Facility Delivery Manager. All mains gas supply pipes up to and including the meter are the responsibility of National Grid. In case of emergency the station has contact details. Natural gas is non-toxic, but large concentrations could cause suffocation. It is highly flammable and leakage from a pipeline could result in an explosive mixture with air. Noise of escaping gas could be sufficient to cause damage to hearing and ear protection must be worn. All persons must be kept 100 metres from the damaged pipeline.

Breckland Forest SSSI work to be carried out between Feb and Sep to avoid nesting birds. All waste material to be removed from site. Remove seedling trees, colonising bramble and invasive species. Rare and scarce plants to be found. No burning.

Dernford Fen SSSI, Timing of Engineering works needs to be considered in releation to breeding birds March to July. Remove invasive species and vegetation outside this zone, should be removed via mechanical methods. Care must be taken to ensure no impact on wildlife.

Rye Meads SSSI. Also designated as a Ramsar Site and a Special Protection Area. Avoid work March to July and also October to march unless you take advice from an ecologist. Ensure ditches are free flowing. Ensure trees do not impede the passage of birds.

Turnford and Cheshunt Pits SSSI. Also designated as a Ramsar site and Special Protection Area. Avoid work March to July and also October to March unless you take advice from a ecologist. Ensure ditches are free flowing. Do not pollute any streams or ditches.

Installed the SSW 900 UTX which include: 2 x HDPE ducts  with dimensional of 0.9m internal and 1.05m external. The space of 1m was put between themselves. Laid on 0.15m shingle at the bottom and 0.15m sorround with the cover on top of 0.3m. All it was encapsulated in with T100 terram. On top was laid a 0.45mm Type 1A3 compacted in 0.15m layers. Above the terram was laid a minimum of 0.3m ballast to underneath the existing sleeper of the rail track which was rainstated to the condition prior to commece of works. The depth of the crown of the HDPE duct to the underneath the existing sleepers is 0.900m and to the top of rail is 1.287m. The direction of the UTX is perpendicular to the direction of the running line and the length is 24m. The owner of this UTX is SSW <South Starfordshire Water>. Contact details are: Steve Everit, 01223 403039 I 07900270073

On top was laid a 0.45mm Type 1A3 compacted in 0.15m layers. Above it was laid a minimum of 0.3m ballast to underneath the existing sleeper of the rail truck which was rainstated to the condition prior to commece of works. The depth of the crown of the 9-way multi duct to the underneath the existing sleepers is 1.05m and to the top of rail is 1.487m. The direction of the UTX is perpendicular to the direction of the running line and the length is 11.315m. This also include the two inspection chambers of Cubis with 1.2m x 1.2m internal installed of the each end of the run of the 9-way multi ducts.The owner is NR as part of the asset of the Railway.

The new cable will not feed NR assets but local businesses. ~
